<stack-static>
    <statement><p><p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>A chemical manufacturer found that the sales figures for a certain chemical X<m>_2</m>O depended on its selling price. At present, the company can sell all of its weekly production of <m>300\text{kg}</m> at a price of <alert>£</alert><m>600</m> per <m>\text{kg}</m>.<nbsp/>
    The company's market research department advised that the amount sold would decrease by only <m>1</m><nbsp/><m>\text{kg}</m> per week for every <alert>£</alert><m>2</m> per <m>\text{kg}</m> increase in the price of X<m>_2</m>O. If the total production costs are made up of
    a fixed cost of <alert>£</alert><m>30000</m> per week, plus <alert>£</alert><m>400</m> per<nbsp/><m>\text{kg}</m> of product.<nbsp/></p>
<p>Let<nbsp/><alert>£</alert><m>x</m> be the new price per <m>\text{kg}</m> of X<m>_2</m>O.<nbsp/>Find a quadratic polynomial <m>P</m> in <m>x</m> which gives the weekly profit.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><m>P =</m> <fillin characters="15" name="ans4"/> </p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Complete the square for the above<nbsp/> expression and hence find</p>
<p/>
<ol>
    <li>the price which maximises the weekly profit on sales of X<m>_2</m>O;<nbsp/> <alert>£</alert><nbsp/><fillin characters="5" name="ans1"/> </li>
    <li>the maximum weekly profit;<nbsp/> <alert>£</alert><fillin characters="5" name="ans2"/> </li>
    <li>the weekly production rate.<nbsp/> <fillin characters="5" name="ans3"/> </li>
</ol></p></statement>
    <solution><p><p/>
<p>Firstly, we must derive the equation for weekly profit. If <m>x</m> is the new price per kg of the chemical, then the new amount produced is</p>
<p><me>300-\frac{(x-600)}{2} = 600-\frac{x}{2}.</me></p>
<p>Now we must work out the profit. This will be what we make from selling the product minus any costs.</p>
<p><me>P = x\left(600-\frac{x}{2}\right)-30000-400\left(600-\frac{x}{2}\right) =</me></p>
<p><me>-\dfrac{x^2}{2}+800x-270000.</me></p>
<p>Completing the square we obtain</p>
<p><me>P = -\frac{1}{2}(x^2-1600x+540000) = -\frac{1}{2}((x-800)^2+540000-800^2 =</me></p>
<p><me> -\frac{1}{2}((x-800)^2+540000-800^2) =-\frac{1}{2}((x-800)^2-100000).</me></p>
<p/>
<ol>
    <li>We want to maximise <m>P</m>. This will occur when <m>(x-800)^2=0</m>, so <m>x=800</m>.</li>
    <li>At <m>x=800</m>, <m>P = 50000</m>.</li>
    <li>The production rate is <m>600-\frac{x}{2}</m>. Subbing in our answer from part 1 we obtain <me>600-\frac{800}{2} = 200.</me></li>
</ol>
<p/>
<p/></p></solution>
    <answer><p><m>-\frac{x^2}{2}+800\cdot x-270000</m></p></answer>
    <answer><p><m>800</m></p></answer>
    <answer><p><m>50000</m></p></answer>
    <answer><p><m>200</m></p></answer>
</stack-static>